<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="80" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,528,447,473]" box="[189,528,447,473]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,528,447,473]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,528,447,473]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">Preliminary considerations</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[187,1401,493,907]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
The 
<typeStatus box="[242,345,493,519]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">holotype</typeStatus>
was not examined; however, according to several caves studies and maps collected by the Association for Mexican Cave Studies (
<collectionCode box="[645,733,529,555]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">AMCS</collectionCode>
, information available at:http://www.mexicancaves.org/) we know that Grutas de Rancho Nuevo are the same as Grutas de 
<collectingCountry box="[994,1159,564,590]" name="Saint Kitts and Nevis" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">San Cristobal</collectingCountry>
; therefore, the male examined here is considered a topotype. This specimen is poorly preserved, without almost all legs, incomplete scutum and broken body. In the present work, we could only illustrate the chelicera, pedipalp, ornamentation of femur and patella IV, and male genitalia in detail. Fortunately, these structures are enough to recognize and diagnose this species. Additionally, 
<bibRefCitation author="Silhavy V." box="[897,1071,705,733]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 194" refId="ref6023" refString="Silhavy V. 1974. Cavernicolous opilionids from Mexico. Subterranean fauna of Mexico. Part. II. Quaderno Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei 171: 175 - 194." type="journal article" year="1974">Šilhavý (1974)</bibRefCitation>
made excellent drawings of dorsal and lateral view of the 
<typeStatus box="[544,650,740,766]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">holotype</typeStatus>
, which are very clear and informative for taxonomic purposes. Finally, 
<bibRefCitation author="Silhavy V." box="[285,461,775,804]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 194" refId="ref6023" refString="Silhavy V. 1974. Cavernicolous opilionids from Mexico. Subterranean fauna of Mexico. Part. II. Quaderno Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei 171: 175 - 194." type="journal article" year="1974">Šilhavý (1974)</bibRefCitation>
, based on immature stages, mentioned two additional records for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Silhavy" authorityYear="1974" box="[1215,1397,775,801]" class="Arachnida" family="Stygnopsidae" genus="Troglostygnopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anophthalma">
<emphasis box="[1215,1397,775,801]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">T. anophthalma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Cueva de la Golondrina and Cueva del Nacimiento del Río San Antonio, both in Bochil, Chiapas. Due to the specificity in cave habitats in these species, it is necessary to collect adults from those caves to corroborate if they are conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Silhavy" authorityYear="1974" box="[687,870,881,907]" class="Arachnida" family="Stygnopsidae" genus="Troglostygnopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anophthalma">
<emphasis box="[687,870,881,907]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">T. anophthalma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or represent undescribed species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,363,946,972]" box="[189,363,946,972]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,363,946,972]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,363,946,972]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">Redescription</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,835,993,1054]" box="[234,298,993,1019]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,298,993,1019]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,835,993,1054]" box="[189,835,1028,1054]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">MEASUREMENTS. Scutum length: 4.9, scutum width: 4.1.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,1093,1155]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
CHELICERA (
<figureCitation box="[330,399,1093,1119]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[198,1389,272,1927]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[198,1389,265,1927]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Troglostygnopsis anophthalma Šilhavý, 1974, ♂, topotype (AMNH). A. Chelicera, mesal view. B. Chelicera, frontal view. C. Pedipalpal femur, mesal view. D. Pedipalpal tibia and tarsus, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5708142" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5708142/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A–B). Scutum/cheliceral hand ratio: 1.37. Basichelicerite long, with diffuse bulla. Cheliceral hand slightly swollen, fixed finger with six teeth distributed evenly throughout, middle one
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5708146" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5708146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5708146/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" startId="5.[189,232,1963,1989]" targetBox="[189,1398,1251,1921]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,1963,2025]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,270,1963,1989]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">Fig. 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Silhavy, 1974" authorityName="Silhavy" authorityYear="1974" box="[282,828,1963,1992]" class="Arachnida" family="Stygnopsidae" genus="Troglostygnopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anophthalma">
<emphasis box="[282,647,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">Troglostygnopsis anophthalma</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Silhavy V." box="[658,828,1963,1992]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 194" refId="ref6023" refString="Silhavy V. 1974. Cavernicolous opilionids from Mexico. Subterranean fauna of Mexico. Part. II. Quaderno Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei 171: 175 - 194." type="journal article" year="1974">Šilhavý, 1974</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, ♂, topotype (AMNH), penis. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1207,1228,1963,1989]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">A</emphasis>
. Dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,209,1998,2024]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">B</emphasis>
. Lateral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[383,404,1998,2024]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">C</emphasis>
. Ventral view. Scale bar in C applicable to all figures.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1399,265,327]" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">biggest; movable finger with three scattered teeth, basalmost and middle ones small and triangular, distal one diffuse.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[188,1400,365,639]" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">
PEDIPALPS (
<figureCitation box="[326,401,366,392]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[198,1389,272,1927]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[198,1389,265,1927]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Troglostygnopsis anophthalma Šilhavý, 1974, ♂, topotype (AMNH). A. Chelicera, mesal view. B. Chelicera, frontal view. C. Pedipalpal femur, mesal view. D. Pedipalpal tibia and tarsus, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5708142" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5708142/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
C–D). Measurements: 2.30/1.00/1.75/1.80/1.00. Trochanter globose, with three ventral spiniform tubercles, apical one very large, dorsally with one spiniform tubercle. Femur slightly compressed laterally, with one ventral and one dorsal row of large spiniform tubercles pointing distally, these tubercles uniformly distributed throughout femur, ventral basalmost one most prominent. Patella with few small spiniform tubercles. Tibia with long armature, with relative sizes of three major tubercles (SST) on mesal side 1 = 3&gt; 2, and on ectal margin 3 = 2&gt; 1, on this segment two small setiferous tubercles between SST 1 and 2, and at apical end of the margin. Tarsus with six major tubercles on mesal side (2&gt; 4 = 5&gt; 6&gt; 1 = 3) and five on ectal side (1&gt; 4&gt; 2 = 3 = 5).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1398,677,774]" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">
LEGS (
<figureCitation box="[265,341,677,704]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1162,1927]" captionTargetId="figure-156@4.[189,1398,1162,1927]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Troglostygnopsis anophthalma Šilhavý, 1974, ♂, topotype (AMNH). A. Apical femur, patella and basal tibia IV. B. Patella IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5708144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5708144/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). All segments very long and slender, femur IV longer than scutum. Ornamentation of femur IV composed of small and scattered tubercles forming longitudinal rows, patella covered with few small tubercles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1401,813,981]" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">
PENIS (
<figureCitation box="[269,342,813,839]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[189,232,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1251,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-283@5.[189,1398,1251,1921]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 3. Troglostygnopsis anophthalma Šilhavý, 1974, ♂, topotype (AMNH), penis. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Ventral view. Scale bar in C applicable to all figures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5708146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5708146/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Pars distalis with an apical concavity, lateral and apical margins softly rolled dorsally. Follis rugose, apices of dorsal bilobular projection long and pointed. One pair of small MS D lateral to base of follis, near to lateral margins of pars distalis. Four pairs of acute MS C forming two irregular rows on lateral sides. MS A+B formed by many spatulate setae, on latero-basal portion of pars distalis, some of them on ventral side. MS E composed of two pairs, MS E1 markedly below level of E2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,362,1020,1081]" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,325,1020,1046]" pageId="6" pageNumber="80">Female</emphasis>
Not examined.
</paragraph>
